HCR <-function(x, alpha=0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4,Flim=1){
  B2B40    <- x/B2B0_target
  if(B2B40>1.){
    maxFabc=Flim
  }else{
    if(alpha<B2B40){
      maxFabc=Flim*((B2B40-alpha)/(1.-alpha))
    }else{
      maxFabc=0.0
    }
  }
  if(B2B40<=(B2B0_lim/B2B0_target))
    maxFabc=0.0
  return(maxFabc)
}


HCR2 <-function(x, alpha=0.05, alpha2 = .2, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4,Flim=1){
  B2B40    <- x/B2B0_target
  # alpha2 is the environmental sensitivity parameter from vulnerability analyses
  if(B2B40>1.){
     if(alpha2<B2B40){
       #maxFabc=Flim*(1-alpha2*(B2B40-1))
        maxFabc=Flim*(exp(-alpha2*(B2B40-1)))
    }
  }else{
    if(alpha<B2B40){
      maxFabc=Flim*((B2B40-alpha)/(1.-alpha))
    }else{
      maxFabc=0.0
    }
  }
  if(B2B40<=(B2B0_lim/B2B0_target))
    maxFabc=0.0
  return(maxFabc)
}

This demo will run example HCR scenarios 1-5 for ACLIM2.

1 ABC+HCR 1: Status quo

This is the basic sloping harvest control rule for groundfish in the EBS. There is a B20% cut-off for SSL (Atka, pollock, P. cod).

B0    <- 3e6  # hypothetical B0 from the stock assessment in 2015
B     <- seq(0,1.2,.001)*B0
B2B0  <- B/B0
Fabc  <- .3 # hypothetical F ABC as determined from the model

# Fadjustment to F_abc, i.e., sloping HCR
F_adj <- unlist(lapply(B2B0, HCR, alpha = 0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4))

plotdat1 <- rbind(data.frame(B2B0=B2B0,
                      F_adj =unlist(lapply(B2B0, HCR, 
                      alpha = 0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.0, B2B0_target=0.4)), 
                      alpha = 0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.0, B2B0_target=0.4, HCR = "HCR1" , HCRscen="HCR1: Status Quo"),
                 data.frame(B2B0=B2B0, 
                            F_adj = unlist(lapply(B2B0, HCR, 
                      alpha = 0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4)),
                      alpha = 0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4, HCR = "HCR1_SSL", HCRscen="HCR1: Status Quo"))


ggplot(plotdat1)+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=B2B0_target),linetype="dashed",size=1.1, color="gray")+
  geom_line(aes(x=B2B0,y=F_adj,color=HCR),size=1)+
  facet_wrap(.~HCRscen)+
  theme_minimal()

2 ABC+HCR 2: Estimate emergency relief financing needs

This simulation set will help us estimate the approximate cost of emergency relief funds by artifically closing the fishery at B25% (mimicking an enconomic driven closure). During recovery we further delay F rate by inducing a stronger alpha during the recovery period (shock to fishery). Implementation of this would be to shorten the recovery period following a shock through a “rainy day” fund.

Details: Sloping HCR, Target = 40%of B0, alpha =0.05, B25% cutoff (initiate emergency $), steeper alpha=0.25 during recovery (recovery occurs at B%40). Calculate difference in catch relative to HCR1 to get an estimate of what $ relief would be needed to supplement the fishery. Apply a steeper slope (alpha) on recovery.

# Fadjustment to F_abc, i.e., sloping HCR
F_adj <- unlist(lapply(B2B0, HCR, alpha = 0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4))

plotdat2 <- rbind(
  # data.frame(B2B0=B2B0,

  #                     alpha = 0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4)), 
  #                     alpha = 0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4, HCR = "HCR1_SSL" , HCRscen="HCR2"),
                  data.frame(B2B0=B2B0,
                      F_adj =unlist(lapply(B2B0, HCR, 
                      alpha = 0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.25, B2B0_target=0.4)),

4 ABC+HCR 4: CE informed sloping rate, e.g., MHW category alpha

Set the target to 40% of B0 (alpha =0.05, blim = 0.2, B_target = 0.4). Below B40 have steeper alphas based on MHW category forecasts, reduces future harvest intensity when conditions are forecast to be poor and could help rebound stocks faster following MHW.

# Fadjustment to F_abc, i.e., sloping HCR
F_adj <- unlist(lapply(B2B0, HCR, alpha = 0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4))


plotdat4 <- rbind(data.frame(B2B0=B2B0,
                      F_adj =unlist(lapply(
                        B2B0, HCR, 
                        alpha = 0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4)), 
                        alpha = 0.05, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4, HCR = "HCR4_1noMHW" , HCRscen="HCR4"),
                 data.frame(B2B0=B2B0,
                          F_adj = unlist(lapply(B2B0, HCR, 
                        alpha = 0.2, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4)),
                        alpha = 0.2, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4, HCR = "HCR4_2smallMHW", HCRscen="HCR4"),
                   data.frame(B2B0=B2B0,
                          F_adj = unlist(lapply(B2B0, HCR, 
                        alpha = 0.4, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4)),
                        alpha = 0.4, B2B0_lim = 0.2, B2B0_target=0.4, HCR = "HCR4_3largeMHW", HCRscen="HCR4"))


ggplot(rbind(plotdat1,plotdat4))+

5 ABC+HCR 5: Reserve for rainy day (climate-vulnerability informed cap effect)

The general idea here is to combine the HCR 4 MHW category 0-4 scaling factor when below B_target (B40) and a cap-like effect when over Btarget. The steepness of that cap effect could be varied based on vulnerability (or approximated via MSE), more sensitive species might need more reserve in the “bank”. Pollock are an example of the HCR in practice (via effects of the 2MT cap + sloping HCR).

After B40 have a slowly sloping Fadj prop to climate variabiltiy? to mimic realized f rates of pollock under the 2 MT cap, i.e., reserve biomass for climate shocks. Set the target to 40% of B0 (alpha =0.05, blim = 0.2, B_target = 0.4). After B40 have a slowly sloping Fadj to mimic realized f rates of pollock under the 2 MT cap, i.e., reserve biomass for climate shocks.
